entry.title: Revert "[LCPP] Call TimingPredictor fallback at window.onload or later LCP"
entry.content:
This reverts commit b05342ab322925f3d7dac43fa6ff7bc60a030a83.



Reason for revert: Fails lcp_critical_path_predictor/timing_predictor_fallback_nohit.php failing "blink_web_tests on Ubuntu-20.04" failing on builder "chromium/ci/WebKit Linux MSAN".



Original change's description:

> [LCPP] Call TimingPredictor fallback at window.onload or later LCP

>

> LCP Critical Path Predictor(LCPP) learns and predicts what element

> would be LCP in the next loading.

> LCP TimingPredictor is a callback API that occurs if a LCP

> element is painted and predicted as actual LCP(LCP can be reported

> twice or more in a load usually.)

> This API would be used to delay P2 tasks to improve the actual LCP

> timing(or this is our Core Web Vital metric).

> Design Doc(google internal):

> https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V5PFwVTDonJ1RE52ZI5WGRihn07atHLApnIWsZ3fgfM/edit?pli=1&resourcekey=0-6we9zT_a97B6ZH0jRalL3g

>

> However there are cases that callback is never called or too late.

> Then, this CL implements the fallback algorithm

> There are 2 cases:

> 1. At window.onload, LCP occurs multiply before window.onload but no

> LCP prediction was hit. Call the fallback at this timing.

> 2. No LCP occur before window.onload. Call the fallback when the first

> LCP occurs after that. There are several factors delay the first LCP

> (resource fetch, paint, visible element is put after onload, etc.)

>

> This CL also move the callback implementation from Document to

> LCPCriticalPathPredictor to clarify the ownership.

>

entry.title: [mullet m3] Remove trigger source from AED::DidAcceptSuggestion.
entry.content:
Removing the trigger source from AED::DidAcceptSuggestion means that

it must always be provided in the AED::OnQuery call. There're 3 places

where we must check that it happens:



* AutofillExternalDelegate: trigger source is always provided the to

AED in the BrowserAutofillManager.

* iOS AutofillAgent: trigger source is always provided in the agent

by calling the AutofillManager::OnAskForValueToFill.

* AwAutofillClient: trigger source is guaranteed to be provided because

the filling goes through BAM::OnAskForValuesToFill.

entry.title: Optimize encoding upload requests
entry.content:
Let R = #renderer_forms and B = #browser_form_fields



Previously FormStructure::EncodeFormFieldsForUpload used to take an

same signature to be considered. This reduces the worst case complexity

to O(B * log(B)) because of prior sorting.

entry.title: [Printing] Implement WebPrintJob::onjobstatechange event
entry.content:
The state transition graph looks as follows:

* A job from a resolved promise is created in kPreliminary state;

* Once this job is acknowledged by the printing pipeline, it moves

either to kPending (if positive) or kAborted (if negative);

* Once printing actually starts, it moves from kPending to kProcessing

* Eventually kProcessing resolves to either kComplete or kAborted.



There's also a state that represents canceled jobs (kCanceled) -- it's

present, but currently unused.

but will be, in particular simplification at computed value time.

entry.title: Remove use of hinted font in FontCache font instantation
entry.content:
Hinted fonts ("screen fonts" vs "printer fonts" in Mac OS lingo) are

currently used in FontCache only when antialiasing is disabled in web

tests and in all other cases we use printer fonts in FontCache, compare

[1]. However, properties screenFont and printerFont are deprecated in

AppKit, compare [2].



Disable used of printer fonts in the remaining cases we had used them,

in testing.



This CL removes hinting usage and deprecated AppKit API calls. Since

hinting is only enabled in some Layout tests, this change should not

affect any web pages.

entry.title: Split LogShadowPredictionComparison()
entry.content:
Splits the function into regex- and ML-related shadow metrics. This

makes for smaller functions and allows using early-returns, which is

particularly helpful since the logic for both depends on feature flags

and build flags.



The CL also fixes the ML shadow metrics. Right now, in builds with

internal patterns, the comparison is done between

heuristic_type(HeuristicSource::kDefault) and

heuristic_type(HeuristicSource::kMachineLearning)

However, when the pattern provider experiment is enabled, kDefault

heuristics are actually not compute and kLegacy is used. See the CL

description of crrev.com/c/5077062 for more context.

This is fixed by emitting into the LegacyPatternSourceToMLModel metric

in this case.

Changing the metric definition is fine, since the ML experiment hasn't

started yet.

entry.title: [blink scheduler] Prioritize navigation IPCs behind a flag
entry.content:
We'd like to prioritize navigation IPCs in the blink scheduler to

prevent navigation latency due to queuing delays. This is especially

important for `scheduler.yield()` (experimental), as continuations are

scheduled at high priority and can block same-process navigations, e.g

refreshing the page. But it is generally not safe to reorder navigation

associated IPCs, so instead we do the following:



1. Mark select navigation IPCs as "[SupportsUrgent]" in mojo

(see crrev.com/c/4977306).



2. Send navigation IPCs in an UrgentMessageScope for foreground main

frames, behind a flag.



3. MainThreadSchedulerImpl implements IPC::UrgentMessageObserver, and

it prioritizes the IPC task queue (the default task queue) while

there are pending urgent IPCs. It does so by keeping count of the

number of pending urgent messages and checking if this has changed

after the current task finishes.



Note: if an urgent message is queued and immediately runs, the queue

is not prioritized.



4. RenderThreadImpl sets the scheduler as the urgent message observer

during initialization (flag guarded).



Note: this feature does not yet work with MBI.



Design doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Pb3lsw1Q2LzLslAGmO_pUR0hDDoSvHhHGCI3pHhJJJY/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: [LCPP] Call TimingPredictor fallback at window.onload or later LCP
entry.content:
LCP Critical Path Predictor(LCPP) learns and predicts what element

would be LCP in the next loading.

LCP TimingPredictor is a callback API that occurs if a LCP

element is painted and predicted as actual LCP(LCP can be reported

twice or more in a load usually.)

This API would be used to delay P2 tasks to improve the actual LCP

timing(or this is our Core Web Vital metric).

Design Doc(google internal):

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V5PFwVTDonJ1RE52ZI5WGRihn07atHLApnIWsZ3fgfM/edit?pli=1&resourcekey=0-6we9zT_a97B6ZH0jRalL3g



However there are cases that callback is never called or too late.

Then, this CL implements the fallback algorithm

There are 2 cases:

1. At window.onload, LCP occurs multiply before window.onload but no

LCP prediction was hit. Call the fallback at this timing.

2. No LCP occur before window.onload. Call the fallback when the first

LCP occurs after that. There are several factors delay the first LCP

(resource fetch, paint, visible element is put after onload, etc.)



This CL also move the callback implementation from Document to

LCPCriticalPathPredictor to clarify the ownership.

entry.title: media/gpu/AV1Decoder: Allow to decode temporal layer stream
entry.content:
AV1Decoder has been denying a temporal layer stream and spatial

layer stream for the principle that a feature is not enabled until

it's needed. Some video conference apps will demand to serve AV1

temporal layer stream recently. So it's time to allow AV1Decoder to

decode a temporal layer stream.



Bug: 1508163
